name: nonyl_cyanide
source: Dreisbach R. R. Physical Properties of Chemical Compounds; Vol. III; American Chemical Society; Washington; 1961.
Reason: The base unit for this compound could be considered as ethane (C2H6) which has a melting point of −183 °C. For each additional methylene group (−CH2−), there is an increase in melting point due to the increase in van der Waals forces. The increase is roughly +5 °C per methylene group. Nonyl cyanide has a total of 9 additional methylene groups compared to ethane. The cyano group (−C≡N) generally increases the melting point due to dipole-dipole interactions and potential for hydrogen bonding with other molecules, contributing with an increase of about +10 °C. Summing these increments together, we would get an estimated melting point shift.

However, as the chain gets longer, the effect of each additional -CH2- group becomes less pronounced due to the overall flexibility and entropy of the chain. Since nonyl cyanide has eight more methylene groups than acetonitrile, we can approximately estimate the melting point increase due to these methylene groups. A conservative estimate might be an increase of 1°C per additional methylene group, considering the diminishing effect. The nitrile group, being a polar and cyano- group, significantly affects the boiling point but less so the melting point, so its effect on the melting point will not be considered significant here. Therefore, the prediction would be the melting point of acetonitrile (-45.7°C) with an addition of approximately 8°C for the eight additional methylene groups.
